# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen-maritime-museum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] Following a competition, the winning design by Alexander Marshall Mackenzie and James Matthews began construction in 1883 and was opened in 7 July 1885.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] There were further additions, again by Mackenzie, in 1901 and 1905, including the addition of a sculpture court.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] In April 2020, the gallery made 50 artworks available digitally via the Smartify app.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] In October 2020, Aberdeen Art Gallery was named one of the five winners of the 2020 ArtFund Museum of the Year Award.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] ArtFund increased the prize money to £200,000 and changed the format of the award to five winners in response to the challenges faced by the museum sector during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Fine Arts collection of the Aberdeen Art Gallery has grown steadily since its foundation in 1885, highlighted with works by such artists as Monet and Renoir as well as more modern artists like John Bulloch Souter, Ian Hamilton Finlay, and James McBey.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The permanent collection includes 18th-century works by Henry Raeburn, William Hogarth, Allan Ramsay and Joshua Reynolds, and 20th-century works by Paul Nash and Francis Bacon, the Post-Impressionists and the Scottish Colourists, as well as applied arts and crafts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The central hall is supported by granite columns in a variety of colours, derived from different quarries in the local area and far beyond.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] At the western end of the building, with a room inside and a monument outside, is a major war memorial.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The war memorial was built in the 1920s as a part of the rapid expansion of the Aberdeen Art Gallery and was funded by a public subscription.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Memorial Court court has a display of several books of remembrance and rolls of honour, commemorating the fallen of World War I, World War II, the Merchant Navy and Fishing Fleets in World War II, and from conflicts after 1945.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] Another addition to the Gallery during this time of rapid expansion was Cowdray Hall.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] Cowdray Hall is a concert venue for music and performances and was opened by King George V and Queen Mary on 25 September 1925.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Gallery was closed for a programme of renovations commencing in 2015.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The £34.6 million redevelopment was designed by Hoskins Architects and carried out by the contractors McLaughlin & Harvey.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-art-gallery] The project won an award from the Scottish Civic Trust for making an outstanding contribution to the quality and appearance of the built environment, as well as the trust's National Panel Special Award.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The building was originally the North Parish Church.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The church was converted to an Arts Centre in 1963.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] By December of that year the Attic Theatre Company were presenting McWhittington, a pantomime over Christmas and New Year.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] As a successor to previous groups such as Aberdeen Children's Theatre established by Catherine Hollingworth, and ACT Aberdeen, Castlegate Arts Limited which operates Aberdeen Arts Centre has charitable status.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The centre is a community-focused arts venue, which aims to provide facilities and opportunities for individuals of all ages, backgrounds and abilities to engage in the performing arts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The theatre is on two levels, with an upper and a lower gallery for audiences.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] There is a small orchestra pit and behind the stage there are dressing and rehearsal rooms for the shows and other projects such as local drama groups.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] In addition the theatre has a large participatory arts programme.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The centre is home to Castlegate Theatre Company (formally established by Annie Inglis), a youth group for teenagers which focuses on devised theatre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] It hosts classes for writers and illustrators, Drama classes, led by Sheena Blackhall, Julie Hutton and Barry Donaldson.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] It hosts touring drama and musical productions and the annual Granite Noir crime writing festival.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] In addition Aberdeen Arts Centre puts on a summer festival known in Aberdeen as 'The Arts Carnival'.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] The building also houses an exhibition area which hosts local and visiting art shows.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] Since 2007 it has hosted an artist in residence programme at the arts centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] A successful campaign was led by Annie Inglis to save the Aberdeen Arts Centre from closure in 1998.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] Aberdeen City Council, as part of a bid to save £17.5m from its annual budget, had decided to cut funding for the centre to save £167,000 annually.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] In March 1998, while recovering in hospital from an asthma attack, Annie had coordinated a 14,500-signature petition to save the centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] This was presented, wrapped in red ribbon to Aberdeen City Council leader, Margaret Smith.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] By June 1998 it was announced that an agreement had been reached between the city council and campaigners who were given until September to form a limited company and to sign a lease with the council as landlords.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] This was then extended by 10 weeks to allow them to meet a fundraising target of £60,000.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] Castlegate Arts Limited was set up on 25 January 1999.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-arts-centre] This is a volunteer led charity which continues to run the centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] The museum is situated on the historic Shiprow in the heart of the city, near the harbour.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] It makes use of a range of buildings including the former Trinity Congregational Church, which was converted to be used as an extension of the museum, and Provost Ross' House, one of the oldest domestic buildings in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] Provost Ross' House was built in 1593 by master-mason Andrew Jamieson and was extended to the south in 1710.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] In 1702 Provost John Ross of Arnage, who was a ship owner, took it as his residence.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] In the 19th century, the building became a set of tenements and became derelict by 1950.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] In 1984, the building was bought by the National Trust for Scotland who leased it to Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-maritime-museum] A few years after buying the building, the council bought the Trinity Congregational Church, aiming to convert it into an extension for the museum.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The centre is a registered charity under Scottish law.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] It is funded through public support and donations from local corporate sponsors, and also includes a café.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The centre is located on Constitution Street.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The building housing the attraction was formerly a depot for Aberdeen's tram network and had previously been based on Justice Mill Lane.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] From 2018 to 2020, the centre operated temporarily from 107 George Street while its Constitution Street premises underwent a multimillion-pound renovation, which was completed in summer 2020.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The centre was first proposed in 1985 with the establishment of the North Scotland Science and Technology Regional Organisation (SATRO).
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] Prior to the establishment of Satrosphere, SATRO North Scotland organised an annual showcase of computers at the Music Hall, with the inaugural event held on 7 December 1986.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] In 1988, SATRO North Scotland received a grant of £60,000 from the Gatsby Charitable Foundation towards the establishment of the centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] A plan for Satrosphere to initially open on an interim basis in a building previously used by Woolmanhill Hospital as an accident and emergency department was unsuccessful in the same year due to budget constraints.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] Following proposals to open the centre in Marywell Street School, a former primary school, and the recently-vacated Hilton Academy, SATRO North Scotland announced in October 1989 that the centre would be located on Justice Mill Lane and commence operations in the following year.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The attraction was opened on 15 February 1990 by Heather Couper.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] It was funded by Grampian Regional Council along with public donations.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] In February 2000, the *Evening Express* reported that Aberdeen City Council had found an owner for the property housing Satrosphere and that the centre would be required to vacate.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] In April 2000, the new location was revealed to be a former tram depot on Constitution Street near Aberdeen Beach.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The new location was opened by Heather Reid on 17 March 2001, following the original site's closure on 9 March.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] In early 2016, the centre was renamed from Satrosphere to Aberdeen Science Centre.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] On 11 November 2018, Aberdeen Science Centre was closed for refurbishment, which included the addition of a mezzanine floor to the building.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] During this time, the centre relocated to George Street for the duration of the renovation, with the new premises opening on 19 November.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] The refurbished centre reopened in November 2020 and was officially reopened in October 2021 by the Astronomer Royal for Scotland Catherine Heymans.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] On 7 August 2021, Aberdeen Science Centre opened a free-to-access branch in the Bon Accord Centre to promote the reopening of its primary location.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aberdeen-science-centre] It subsequently closed and was replaced with a Superdry shop in 2025.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The park can be accessed from Mintlaw via Station Road or Nether Aden Road, and hosts an annual pipe band contest which attracts bands from across Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The Aberdeenshire Farming Museum comprises two main features.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The early 19th-century semicircular Home Farm steading presents interpretations of life on the 20th-century Aden Estate, including through the use of costumed guides.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The "Weel Vrocht Grun" (well-worked ground) contains displays on regional farming history and agricultural innovation over the last two centuries.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The Hareshowe Working Farm was moved to Aden Country Park in the early 1990s.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The farmhouse has been restored to a 1950s appearance, with guided tours providing demonstrations of cooking and farm activities.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The mansion house was originally granted to the Keith family in 1324, before passing to the Russells of Montcoffer.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] It was said to have been beautiful prior to its ruin.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] Alexander Russell of Montcoffer (1723–98) later purchased the Aden estate in 1758 from James Ferguson of Kinmundy.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] John Smith reconstructed the mansion in 1832 with "a magnificent balustraded west wing and Doric-columned, domed, projecting west bow".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] Alexander Russell's great-great-grandson, Sidney Russell (1895–1965), was the last Russell laird to live at Aden.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] He sold the estate in 1937 and moved to Dorset.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] The Barony of Aden is still held by the Russell family.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] During World War II, it was used as an army barracks, and it is said that the interior decoration was damaged and lost its lustre during this period.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] After the war, the house was left to fall into ruin.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/aden-country-park] As of 1990, only its outer walls remained standing.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The four-storey tower is 68 feet (21 m) high, excluding the attic.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The building is made from coursed rubble and measures 62.5 by 39.5 feet (19.1 by 12.0 m) in size.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The building has been extensively re-fenestrated during its history, but retains some internal medieval features.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] It was originally built as part of a line of fortifications defending the north shore of the Firth of Forth.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Several 19th-century works, including Groome's Gazetteer, date the tower to the year 1223.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Archaeological investigations from the early 1990s date the original fortified house to the early 14th century, where it had a cellar that sometimes served as a pit prison.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] By the mid-14th century, it had been enlarged with a great hall and rose to three storeys in height, with the entrance on the first floor.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] In the 15th century, it was further enlarged to four/five levels while retaining its first-floor access.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Late in the 16th century, ground-floor access was probably added.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] John Erskine, 6th Earl of Mar, built a very large mansion (Alloa House) in 1710 that incorporated the tower as its annexe.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Mar made plans to remodel the tower's interior, but it is unclear what changes were actually made.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The house burned down in 1800 and was rebuilt by George Angus in 1834–1838 for the 9th Earl.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Currently, the tower is a public attraction and hosts events for different holidays like Easter and Christmas.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] In February 1497, the gardener of Alloa brought trees to plant in the garden at Stirling Castle.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Margaret Tudor met the Chancellor James Beaton at Alloa on 11 July 1524, to discuss transferring power from Regent Albany to the young James V.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] James V and Mary of Guise came to Alloa by boat on 7 April 1540.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Mary, Queen of Scots visited John, Lord Erskine and his wife Annabell Murray at Alloa on 16 June 1562, and again in May 1565.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Mary returned to Alloa on 28 July 1566, soon after the birth of Prince James.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Some sources say the French ambassador Michel de Castelnau came with the Bishop of Ross to Alloa to congratulate Mary on her safe delivery.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] They would later exchange dozens of letters in cipher code.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Mary's visit to Alloa subsequently attracted the attention of her enemies, and the details are disputed.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] A chronicle mentions that she left her servants at Newhaven, and took a small boat to Alloa, crewed by "simple men of seafare trade".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] According to George Buchanan and the "Book of Articles", the crew were "notorious pirates", associates of the Earl of Bothwell including William and Edmund Blackadder.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] On 28 July at Alloa, Mary announced her plans to travel to Jedburgh to hold justice courts.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] She on 31 July to Annabell Murray's brother-in-law, the Laird of Abercairney, on behalf of the evicted widow of one of his tenants.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Claude Nau wrote that Mary's only companions at Alloa were her ladies in waiting and the Earl of Mar, and Darnley only made a brief visit.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] When Darnley came to Alloa by road, Mary told him to go away.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Mary enjoyed dancing at Alloa during this visit.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] It is also said she went to Stirling in disguise dressed as an ordinary townswoman "in homely sort" and joined in a dance around the Market Cross.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] James VI of Scotland stayed at Alloa for four days in August 1580.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] In December 1592, the widower John Erskine, Earl of Mar, married Marie Stewart, a daughter of Esmé Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] James VI and Anne of Denmark gave the bride clothes, and wedding celebrations were held at Alloa following the marriage at Holyroodhouse.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] One version of the *Memoir* of David Moysie mentions that the King and Queen were "in Alloway the earle of Mars house at the bankett at Yuill and at Nursemes".
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] *Newersmes* was a Scots Language word for New Year's Day.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Festivities, customarily held at a bridegroom's family home known as the *infare*, were mentioned by one of the invited guests, the courtier John Elphinstone.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Costume was bought for a masque at Alloa in which Anne of Denmark performed, dancing in silk taffeta and "gold tock", a kind of tinsel fabric.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The party was cut short when Sir John Carmichael and Sir George Home arrived from Edinburgh with news of the crisis caused by the discovery of the Spanish blanks.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] In England, after the Union of the Crowns, Anne would further develop the masque form to articulate her queenship.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] John Erskine, the second earl of Mar, is known to have been involved in two trials.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The first, in 1596, concerned Margaret Crawford.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] She had been accused of practicing mass in the Catholic way, and John Erskine was asked to raise a commission for a trial.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] The second trial, held from 1613–1614, concerned the Erskine of Dun siblings: Robert, Anna, Helen, and Isobel.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] They were found guilty of consorting with a witch, Janet Irvine, in order to poison their nephews so that they could claim their inheritance.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Between May and August 1658, many residents of Alloa were also involved in a witch-hunt.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Margaret Duchell was arrested by the Alloa kirk session, and, after interrogation, confessed to making a pact with the devil, harming others, and attending witches sabbaths with six other witches.
[src:aberdeen-maritime-museum/alloa-tower] Four of these six; Margaret Taylor, Bessie Paton, Janet Black, and Katherine Rainie, were arrested between June and August.
